WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.480 --> 00:00:02.350
MALE SPEAKER: Good afternoon,
everyone.

00:00:02.350 --> 00:00:05.560
Thank you for making your way up
into the inner recesses of

00:00:05.560 --> 00:00:06.660
the Googleplex here.

00:00:06.660 --> 00:00:09.900
We're very pleased to host a
true inventor in our midst

00:00:09.900 --> 00:00:11.580
today for Talks at Google.

00:00:11.580 --> 00:00:13.210
We actually have Brett
Stern here.

00:00:13.210 --> 00:00:16.800
He's an industrial designer and
inventor, currently living

00:00:16.800 --> 00:00:17.770
in Portland, Oregon.

00:00:17.770 --> 00:00:20.700
So he has the whole Portlandia
thing going on.

00:00:20.700 --> 00:00:22.860
His contributions span a
variety of industries--

00:00:22.860 --> 00:00:25.780
anything from the textile and
pharmaceutical industries to

00:00:25.780 --> 00:00:27.040
consumer packaged goods.

00:00:27.040 --> 00:00:29.560
Things like Beer Chips, which
are actually quite amazing.

00:00:29.560 --> 00:00:32.100
He speaks to us today about
his new book, which is

00:00:32.100 --> 00:00:35.800
entitled "Inventors at Work." In
it, he profiles a series of

00:00:35.800 --> 00:00:39.260
inventors across industries,
looks for commonalities, does

00:00:39.260 --> 00:00:42.730
some in person and phone
interviews, and creates this

00:00:42.730 --> 00:00:46.340
book that is now part of the "At
Work" series, continuing

00:00:46.340 --> 00:00:49.180
the tradition of coders
at work and so forth.

00:00:49.180 --> 00:00:52.990
He describes common threads and
Eureka moments from people

00:00:52.990 --> 00:00:56.220
like Steve Wozniak and the
inventor of the Leatherman,

00:00:56.220 --> 00:00:59.250
which are both very near and
dear to the tech work that we

00:00:59.250 --> 00:01:00.300
do here at Google.

00:01:00.300 --> 00:01:02.565
So without further ado, please
join me in welcoming Brett to

00:01:02.565 --> 00:01:03.811
the Googleplex.

00:01:03.811 --> 00:01:07.420
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:07.420 --> 00:01:09.610
BRETT STERN: So, I am an
industrial designer, and most

00:01:09.610 --> 00:01:12.320
people have no idea
what that is.

00:01:12.320 --> 00:01:14.700
They go to the store, they buy
stuff, and they don't really

00:01:14.700 --> 00:01:16.130
think what's behind it.

00:01:16.130 --> 00:01:18.660
When I try to explain what an
industrial designer is,

00:01:18.660 --> 00:01:21.300
there's this very vague look
on people's faces.

00:01:21.300 --> 00:01:23.130
And then I say, well,
you know an iPhone

00:01:23.130 --> 00:01:24.550
is designed so great?

00:01:24.550 --> 00:01:26.030
And they're like, yeah,
we understand that!

00:01:26.030 --> 00:01:28.420
And then they say, well, did
you design the iPhone?

00:01:28.420 --> 00:01:30.810
And then I have to say no, and
they're sort of upset.

00:01:30.810 --> 00:01:35.300
And so I've learned over years
and come to accept that I tell

00:01:35.300 --> 00:01:36.670
people now that I'm
an inventor.

00:01:36.670 --> 00:01:38.710
And everyone knows
one inventor.

00:01:38.710 --> 00:01:40.120
They sort of have these romantic
thoughts in their

00:01:40.120 --> 00:01:43.570
head of a lone guy
in a garage--

00:01:43.570 --> 00:01:45.870
maybe crazy, or maybe he's a
genius, they don't really

00:01:45.870 --> 00:01:49.290
know-- but sort of working the
late night oil, and just sort

00:01:49.290 --> 00:01:52.070
of making something new to make
the world a better place,

00:01:52.070 --> 00:01:54.160
make our lives easier,
and so forth.

00:01:54.160 --> 00:01:56.420
So I do have that background.

00:01:56.420 --> 00:01:59.940
I am an industrial designer,
though I like to sort of step

00:01:59.940 --> 00:02:03.080
back and work on projects before
you even know what the

00:02:03.080 --> 00:02:03.800
problem is.

00:02:03.800 --> 00:02:07.440
And that's sort of how I work
the inventor side in.

00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:10.440
So this project came along,
the "Inventors at Work,"

00:02:10.440 --> 00:02:11.870
Apress the publisher.

00:02:11.870 --> 00:02:14.720
They've done a number of
books in this series.

00:02:14.720 --> 00:02:18.300
And so they just said, hey,
go figure the book out.

00:02:18.300 --> 00:02:21.110
Work within the format we're
doing, which is go out and

00:02:21.110 --> 00:02:23.990
find people within that
industry, interview them,

00:02:23.990 --> 00:02:26.780
whatever questions you want,
and then sort of edit these

00:02:26.780 --> 00:02:29.800
conversations to do
whatever you want.

00:02:29.800 --> 00:02:32.940
I read a great deal about
inventors, about creative

00:02:32.940 --> 00:02:35.550
people, and the process
and so forth.

00:02:35.550 --> 00:02:39.590
I feel I'm able to go from
surgical instruments to potato

00:02:39.590 --> 00:02:42.300
chips easily, because I
understand the process of what

00:02:42.300 --> 00:02:44.630
it is to be a creative person
and how to think

00:02:44.630 --> 00:02:46.060
broadly over that.

00:02:46.060 --> 00:02:49.250
And so my goal of this project
was not to talk to these

00:02:49.250 --> 00:02:53.260
inventors about their products,
which generally most

00:02:53.260 --> 00:02:56.350
stories talk about, but
rather the process.

00:02:56.350 --> 00:02:58.430
So it wasn't about the product
they were doing, but about the

00:02:58.430 --> 00:03:00.520
process that they go
through every day.

00:03:00.520 --> 00:03:04.370
And the goal was, what I was
trying to learn and what I'm

00:03:04.370 --> 00:03:06.900
trying to convey to the reader,
is what are those--

00:03:06.900 --> 00:03:08.140
are there commonalities?

00:03:08.140 --> 00:03:11.590
Are there certain traits that
we inventive people, we

00:03:11.590 --> 00:03:16.170
creative people have inside of
us that somehow makes us

00:03:16.170 --> 00:03:18.500
different from all the other
kids on the block?

00:03:18.500 --> 00:03:22.330
And so, going into it, I would
sort of start this generic

00:03:22.330 --> 00:03:27.190
question, and try to dial down
and try to seek what they were

00:03:27.190 --> 00:03:29.020
really thinking,
how they think.

00:03:29.020 --> 00:03:31.660
And it's not so much thinking
when they're behind their

00:03:31.660 --> 00:03:34.410
keyboard or their desk or their
drawing board, but how

00:03:34.410 --> 00:03:37.160
they're thinking during the day,
at night, when they're

00:03:37.160 --> 00:03:39.920
sleeping, when they're
on top of a mountain.

00:03:39.920 --> 00:03:43.730
Just how they think, and what
their process is to go from

00:03:43.730 --> 00:03:49.290
point A to point B. And so my
presentation is going to be

00:03:49.290 --> 00:03:51.890
what I learned from doing this
book, and what these

00:03:51.890 --> 00:03:54.130
commonalities are,
and so forth.

00:03:54.130 --> 00:03:58.290
Now, when I started the book,
I had carte blanche to just

00:03:58.290 --> 00:04:00.600
find any inventor that I wanted,
and that's sort of

00:04:00.600 --> 00:04:02.060
like the dream list.

00:04:02.060 --> 00:04:05.630
And the reality is, when you say
inventors, you know their

00:04:05.630 --> 00:04:07.510
inventions, but you
don't really know

00:04:07.510 --> 00:04:08.605
the person, the inventor.

00:04:08.605 --> 00:04:10.700
I mean, we know Thomas Edison.

00:04:10.700 --> 00:04:13.980
We may know Steve Wozniak and a
few other technical people.

00:04:13.980 --> 00:04:16.480
But we really don't know
the person behind it.

00:04:16.480 --> 00:04:22.160
So my process was to just start
with this empty slate,

00:04:22.160 --> 00:04:26.020
and put down industries or
technologies or products that

00:04:26.020 --> 00:04:27.070
I wanted to know.

00:04:27.070 --> 00:04:29.120
Obvious electronics--

00:04:29.120 --> 00:04:30.480
computers and things
like that.

00:04:30.480 --> 00:04:36.420
Transportation, medical,
communication, fun, sports,

00:04:36.420 --> 00:04:39.250
materials, whatever it was.

00:04:39.250 --> 00:04:42.710
And then my process was to go
out there and find these

00:04:42.710 --> 00:04:43.980
people and do the process.

00:04:43.980 --> 00:04:47.430
And the process was just sort
of going online and frankly,

00:04:47.430 --> 00:04:52.300
Googling the companies or the
people that I wanted to do,

00:04:52.300 --> 00:04:57.710
and then just continuously
research who these people

00:04:57.710 --> 00:05:01.170
were, finding everything out
there was about them.

00:05:01.170 --> 00:05:03.180
And then I would be interviewing
them, mostly on

00:05:03.180 --> 00:05:07.070
the phone, through Skype,
through videoconferencing,

00:05:07.070 --> 00:05:10.270
putting all these conversations
into

00:05:10.270 --> 00:05:13.870
conversations, having them
transcribed, then editing them

00:05:13.870 --> 00:05:17.620
out, creating Word documents,
sitting in an Ergon chair with

00:05:17.620 --> 00:05:19.930
my noise cancelling
headsets on.

00:05:19.930 --> 00:05:22.170
And while I was doing this,
I just realized all the

00:05:22.170 --> 00:05:25.520
technology and all the
inventions that allowed me to

00:05:25.520 --> 00:05:28.960
sit in a chair in my room all
by myself to sort of find

00:05:28.960 --> 00:05:31.300
these people out there
was just amazing.

00:05:31.300 --> 00:05:34.680
So the presentation will talk
about these commonalities.

00:05:38.690 --> 00:05:39.630
So dreaming.

00:05:39.630 --> 00:05:41.640
"When I was young, I would go
to sleep thinking about

00:05:41.640 --> 00:05:44.820
computer programs or computer
hardware problems or math

00:05:44.820 --> 00:05:45.600
problems in school.

00:05:45.600 --> 00:05:48.480
Sleep and think, and think as
I fell asleep, working the

00:05:48.480 --> 00:05:50.970
variables in my head, seeing
the lines of code.

00:05:50.970 --> 00:05:52.540
And then I would wake up in
the middle of the night

00:05:52.540 --> 00:05:55.170
sometimes and have a solution
that would save one line of

00:05:55.170 --> 00:05:56.030
code in a program.

00:05:56.030 --> 00:05:58.190
So I believe very much that
your mind is working while

00:05:58.190 --> 00:06:00.070
you're dreaming."
Steve Wozniak.

00:06:00.070 --> 00:06:02.560
I mean, we all know
who this guy was.

00:06:02.560 --> 00:06:05.820
And of all these common traits,
I think the biggest

00:06:05.820 --> 00:06:08.110
one that makes us unique
as creative

00:06:08.110 --> 00:06:09.750
people is this dreaming.

00:06:09.750 --> 00:06:14.210
And somehow, dreaming has a
negative connotation in

00:06:14.210 --> 00:06:15.070
today's society--

00:06:15.070 --> 00:06:17.670
like, you're daydreaming, you're
wandering off, you're

00:06:17.670 --> 00:06:20.520
not focused, just pay
attention here.

00:06:20.520 --> 00:06:21.910
That you can't pay attention.

00:06:21.910 --> 00:06:23.900
But dreaming is just
sort of essential.

00:06:23.900 --> 00:06:26.530
I mean, it's somewhat of a
childlike thing, because we do

00:06:26.530 --> 00:06:27.640
it all as a child.

00:06:27.640 --> 00:06:29.330
And hopefully as an
adult, we can

00:06:29.330 --> 00:06:30.710
continue that in the process.

00:06:30.710 --> 00:06:34.340
So this daydreaming, or this
dreaming, is really a very

00:06:34.340 --> 00:06:35.200
important quality.

00:06:35.200 --> 00:06:38.410
And this is, I think, out of
all these traits is the one

00:06:38.410 --> 00:06:43.270
thing that you cannot be taught
or educated or advance.

00:06:43.270 --> 00:06:45.160
It's either in you and
you allow it to

00:06:45.160 --> 00:06:46.950
happen or you don't.

00:06:46.950 --> 00:06:50.530
And I think that's what makes us
as creative inventive types

00:06:50.530 --> 00:06:54.430
different from the rest of
the people out there.

00:06:54.430 --> 00:06:55.350
So pondering.

00:06:55.350 --> 00:06:57.480
"I know that if I go to a
seminar or a conference to

00:06:57.480 --> 00:07:00.290
hear someone talk, I'll drift
off, because the mechanism, or

00:07:00.290 --> 00:07:02.300
the chemistry, or the approach
that they're talking about

00:07:02.300 --> 00:07:04.830
spurs an idea that might
be useful in solving or

00:07:04.830 --> 00:07:06.800
addressing some of the
problems I have.

00:07:06.800 --> 00:07:09.130
Even when it's not really what
the guy or lady is talking

00:07:09.130 --> 00:07:12.390
about specifically, but
something analogous to that."

00:07:12.390 --> 00:07:13.610
So the pondering.

00:07:13.610 --> 00:07:14.600
This is Al Maurice.

00:07:14.600 --> 00:07:18.410
He's a polymer chemist at Dow
Chemical, and what he

00:07:18.410 --> 00:07:22.450
developed was the polymers to
go from oil based paints to

00:07:22.450 --> 00:07:23.910
acrylic based paints.

00:07:23.910 --> 00:07:28.340
Now, if you're at a certain
age, there was always oil

00:07:28.340 --> 00:07:28.980
based paints.

00:07:28.980 --> 00:07:31.890
And if you went down to the
garage, there was a coffee can

00:07:31.890 --> 00:07:35.840
with a stiff brush in there all
sort of stuck together.

00:07:35.840 --> 00:07:38.070
And if you walked into a room
that was just painted with oil

00:07:38.070 --> 00:07:40.670
based paints, you would smell
the fumes, and you'd get a

00:07:40.670 --> 00:07:42.540
headache or you'd drift
off or something.

00:07:42.540 --> 00:07:45.950
Well, this guy figured out all
the polymer chemistry.

00:07:45.950 --> 00:07:48.860
So he wasn't developing paint,
but it was the thing to go

00:07:48.860 --> 00:07:50.480
into the thing to the thing.

00:07:50.480 --> 00:07:54.090
And so it was just so far
removed, but his days were

00:07:54.090 --> 00:07:57.110
just mixing chemicals together
to get to this final point.

00:07:57.110 --> 00:07:59.460
And so he'd been working,
literally, on the same problem

00:07:59.460 --> 00:08:03.100
for the last 30 years to make
water-based paints.

00:08:03.100 --> 00:08:06.550
And the fun part of asking
these people just general

00:08:06.550 --> 00:08:09.620
questions is I actually got
to ask him the process.

00:08:09.620 --> 00:08:13.050
And he'd go, well, we mix all
these things together, and we

00:08:13.050 --> 00:08:15.250
basically put the paint
out there, and then

00:08:15.250 --> 00:08:16.220
we'd watch it dry.

00:08:16.220 --> 00:08:19.750
And I was like, you actually got
paid to watch paint dry.

00:08:19.750 --> 00:08:22.890
And so he really did get paid
to watch paint dry.

00:08:22.890 --> 00:08:24.100
Just fascinating.

00:08:24.100 --> 00:08:28.730
It just really used the process
of creativity to

00:08:28.730 --> 00:08:32.039
develop all these things.

00:08:32.039 --> 00:08:34.465
Also, some of these people were
corporate people, some

00:08:34.465 --> 00:08:36.549
were academia, some
governmental,

00:08:36.549 --> 00:08:38.700
some guys in a garage.

00:08:38.700 --> 00:08:42.440
Al works at Dow Chemical,
certainly a well known company

00:08:42.440 --> 00:08:46.110
that promotes technology and
promotes innovation.

00:08:46.110 --> 00:08:48.790
What was interesting, that there
are companies out there,

00:08:48.790 --> 00:08:52.290
and I'm sure Google is very
similar, that once you become

00:08:52.290 --> 00:08:54.680
successful in what you're
doing, you go up

00:08:54.680 --> 00:08:56.000
the corporate ladder.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:58.020
But companies like Dow,
companies like Corning,

00:08:58.020 --> 00:09:01.210
companies like IBM and GE, they
allow their technical

00:09:01.210 --> 00:09:04.700
people to advance and go up
the corporate ladder, but

00:09:04.700 --> 00:09:08.110
still stay, in a sense, in the
lab doing their research.

00:09:08.110 --> 00:09:09.650
So they didn't have to
become a manager.

00:09:09.650 --> 00:09:11.070
If they wanted to,
they could do it.

00:09:11.070 --> 00:09:14.190
And I think Al, at some point,
had become a manager.

00:09:14.190 --> 00:09:16.780
But really, he was managing
the innovation, the

00:09:16.780 --> 00:09:17.600
creativity.

00:09:17.600 --> 00:09:19.830
But he is still in
the lab every day

00:09:19.830 --> 00:09:23.060
mixing things together.

00:09:23.060 --> 00:09:26.070
"To prospective inventors, I say
rule one is perseverance.

00:09:26.070 --> 00:09:27.930
If you're working on an
invention, at some point,

00:09:27.930 --> 00:09:30.540
you're probably going to think
about giving up and going on

00:09:30.540 --> 00:09:31.690
to something else.

00:09:31.690 --> 00:09:34.310
I realize there's a fine line
between perseverance and

00:09:34.310 --> 00:09:35.960
failure to accept reality.

00:09:35.960 --> 00:09:38.260
But I recommend that you lean
toward staying with it too

00:09:38.260 --> 00:09:41.130
long rather than giving up too
soon." That's Tim Leatherman,

00:09:41.130 --> 00:09:43.000
who happens to be in Portland,
Oregon, who I

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:44.680
interviewed in person.

00:09:44.680 --> 00:09:47.450
And so I'm sure everyone knows
the Leatherman tool.

00:09:47.450 --> 00:09:49.760
There actually is a guy named
Tim Leatherman behind

00:09:49.760 --> 00:09:51.130
Leatherman Tools.

00:09:51.130 --> 00:09:53.370
And they actually have developed
leather working

00:09:53.370 --> 00:09:55.180
tools, but no one
ever buys them.

00:09:55.180 --> 00:09:58.660
So he was trained as a
mechanical engineer, travelled

00:09:58.660 --> 00:10:02.480
around in the early '70s in
Europe with his soon to be

00:10:02.480 --> 00:10:06.050
wife, bought a car, stayed
in cheap hotels.

00:10:06.050 --> 00:10:08.530
And he was always fixing this
car or fixing the plumbing in

00:10:08.530 --> 00:10:11.000
these cheap hotels traveling
around Europe.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:13.750
And so he was always looking for
pliers or screwdrivers or

00:10:13.750 --> 00:10:16.740
tools to sort of fix
his daily routine.

00:10:16.740 --> 00:10:19.090
And so when he came back, even
though he was trained as an

00:10:19.090 --> 00:10:22.330
engineer and actually worked
when he got out of school in

00:10:22.330 --> 00:10:25.480
engineering, he decided he
wanted to develop this

00:10:25.480 --> 00:10:28.490
multi-purpose tool that has
now become part of the

00:10:28.490 --> 00:10:31.570
vernacular, and actually spent
seven years in his garage,

00:10:31.570 --> 00:10:34.550
from the time of making his
first prototype to then

00:10:34.550 --> 00:10:36.210
actually commercialization.

00:10:36.210 --> 00:10:39.400
So here's a man, for seven
years, just living--

00:10:39.400 --> 00:10:42.640
he was not working, just going
broke trying to develop the

00:10:42.640 --> 00:10:44.060
Leatherman tool.

00:10:44.060 --> 00:10:46.230
And now his proudest achievement
is actually not

00:10:46.230 --> 00:10:47.950
the tool, but they do all their

00:10:47.950 --> 00:10:49.290
manufacturing in Portland.

00:10:49.290 --> 00:10:51.980
So he has 300 people there in
Portland and making the thing.

00:10:51.980 --> 00:10:54.950
And so he feels the greatest
thing that he's done is

00:10:54.950 --> 00:10:58.280
actually employing 300 people
to produce his product.

00:10:58.280 --> 00:10:59.930
"Failure is a way of learning.

00:10:59.930 --> 00:11:02.050
What may be considered failures
are actually other

00:11:02.050 --> 00:11:06.140
great ideas." Anybody
know Robert Denard?

00:11:06.140 --> 00:11:07.670
He invented RAM memory.

00:11:07.670 --> 00:11:09.050
I mean, memory.

00:11:09.050 --> 00:11:10.840
It's what we all live
on right now.

00:11:10.840 --> 00:11:11.990
He's 84-years-old.

00:11:11.990 --> 00:11:14.340
He's a senior fellow
at IBM, still in

00:11:14.340 --> 00:11:16.000
there every day working.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:17.750
Pretty amazing.

00:11:17.750 --> 00:11:21.160
Now, when you invent something,
there's always this

00:11:21.160 --> 00:11:22.200
prior art--

00:11:22.200 --> 00:11:23.770
what someone did beforehand.

00:11:23.770 --> 00:11:27.410
And what was fascinating talking
to Bob was what he

00:11:27.410 --> 00:11:29.480
did, there really was nothing
before there.

00:11:29.480 --> 00:11:31.260
Everything was a bunch
of tubes and

00:11:31.260 --> 00:11:32.820
vacuums and so forth.

00:11:32.820 --> 00:11:36.180
So he really is the first one
who created something new,

00:11:36.180 --> 00:11:38.860
which is just such a
rarity these days.

00:11:38.860 --> 00:11:43.380
And I think one of things we
get hung up as people, as a

00:11:43.380 --> 00:11:46.040
society, is failure
is a bad thing.

00:11:46.040 --> 00:11:47.530
But failure is such
a great thing.

00:11:47.530 --> 00:11:50.610
You learn what's not working for
that particular problem,

00:11:50.610 --> 00:11:53.710
but you have that experience,
and you go on and apply that

00:11:53.710 --> 00:11:56.910
knowledge to something else
at a future point.

00:11:56.910 --> 00:11:58.170
Self motivation.

00:11:58.170 --> 00:12:00.560
"You know, when there's a
certain joy to what you do,

00:12:00.560 --> 00:12:03.190
and when you have this certain
energy, that's

00:12:03.190 --> 00:12:04.660
what makes me happy.

00:12:04.660 --> 00:12:06.010
Doing these things
made me happy.

00:12:06.010 --> 00:12:07.180
That was the real motivation.

00:12:07.180 --> 00:12:11.380
It made me happy." So Gary
Mickelson is a spinal surgeon.

00:12:11.380 --> 00:12:14.900
And just to give you an idea how
successful he was, he sold

00:12:14.900 --> 00:12:16.870
all his patents-- about 250--

00:12:16.870 --> 00:12:19.530
in 2005 for $1.4 billion.

00:12:19.530 --> 00:12:23.670
Totally changed the way
everything did.

00:12:23.670 --> 00:12:27.450
What was interesting, here
is a man who is totally

00:12:27.450 --> 00:12:31.630
successful in what he's doing,
but totally insecure about was

00:12:31.630 --> 00:12:33.830
he ever really successful
in doing this?

00:12:33.830 --> 00:12:36.830
And he said, every time he would
create something, and

00:12:36.830 --> 00:12:39.400
when he was a resident, all the
doctors would say, don't

00:12:39.400 --> 00:12:41.140
do that, you're wrong,
you're stupid.

00:12:41.140 --> 00:12:43.340
Do it my way that I've always
done it before.

00:12:43.340 --> 00:12:46.380
And the biggest thing he said
that the doctors told him, the

00:12:46.380 --> 00:12:49.580
biggest reservation they had is,
like, don't kill anybody.

00:12:49.580 --> 00:12:52.820
And so when we invent something,
we think, oh, well,

00:12:52.820 --> 00:12:55.910
that program won't work, or that
toy won't work, whatever.

00:12:55.910 --> 00:12:59.610
Well, he could paralyze
people or kill people.

00:12:59.610 --> 00:13:02.260
So it's just fascinating that
he really changed the whole

00:13:02.260 --> 00:13:06.510
subject matter and the whole
range of medical procedures.

00:13:06.510 --> 00:13:11.760
Seek inspiration outside your
field. "Solutions kind of

00:13:11.760 --> 00:13:13.590
flash into your brain
at some point.

00:13:13.590 --> 00:13:16.250
I can't really explain what my
subconscious activity is,

00:13:16.250 --> 00:13:18.010
especially these days.

00:13:18.010 --> 00:13:20.910
I like to spend a lot of my time
on my farm pushing rocks

00:13:20.910 --> 00:13:22.170
around with my tractor.

00:13:22.170 --> 00:13:25.830
It's a background process or
subconscious process I really

00:13:25.830 --> 00:13:26.640
cannot explain.

00:13:26.640 --> 00:13:29.270
Usually it's related to having
a problem I want to solve.

00:13:29.270 --> 00:13:31.760
I don't sit back and dream up
solutions to things that don't

00:13:31.760 --> 00:13:34.150
have a problem yet, but when
faced with a problem, usually

00:13:34.150 --> 00:13:37.190
the solutions, in my field, at
least, come pretty quickly.

00:13:37.190 --> 00:13:39.030
I can't give you a recipe
for invention.

00:13:39.030 --> 00:13:40.220
That's impossible."

00:13:40.220 --> 00:13:41.490
So Eric was a physicist.

00:13:41.490 --> 00:13:44.480
He was a professor at Columbia
doing research.

00:13:44.480 --> 00:13:47.360
And then in the early '80s,
got brought out to Jet

00:13:47.360 --> 00:13:50.820
Propulsion Labs to work on
satellite camera systems.

00:13:50.820 --> 00:13:52.720
At the time, they were
all film based, and

00:13:52.720 --> 00:13:54.010
used big heavy batteries.

00:13:54.010 --> 00:13:56.130
And they were shooting two,
three satellites up, and they

00:13:56.130 --> 00:13:57.580
needed to record everything.

00:13:57.580 --> 00:14:00.805
What he developed was
a digital camera.

00:14:00.805 --> 00:14:02.760
Every digital camera on
your phone now is

00:14:02.760 --> 00:14:03.970
stuff that he developed.

00:14:03.970 --> 00:14:06.240
So he did this back
in the '80s.

00:14:06.240 --> 00:14:08.410
When we talk to him in this day
and age, I said, did you

00:14:08.410 --> 00:14:16.760
ever think 30 years later, 20
years later, that every phone

00:14:16.760 --> 00:14:17.480
would have a camera?

00:14:17.480 --> 00:14:22.820
And he's still redeveloping this
technology today, and now

00:14:22.820 --> 00:14:23.570
they're on cameras.

00:14:23.570 --> 00:14:25.890
But he's saying, eventually,
you're going to be swallowing

00:14:25.890 --> 00:14:28.280
these cameras and looking
inside of you and taking

00:14:28.280 --> 00:14:30.680
pictures, which their
researchers are doing already.

00:14:30.680 --> 00:14:33.008
So it's just fascinating.

00:14:33.008 --> 00:14:36.350
AUDIENCE: I was just curious,
was the camera-- did it come

00:14:36.350 --> 00:14:40.940
from an inspiration outside
of what he was working on?

00:14:40.940 --> 00:14:43.180
BRETT STERN: You know, I don't
really know where he found

00:14:43.180 --> 00:14:44.230
that inspiration from.

00:14:44.230 --> 00:14:45.020
It's a good question.

00:14:45.020 --> 00:14:49.400
But I think what he was sort of
saying there-- that because

00:14:49.400 --> 00:14:53.100
he was a physicist, he didn't
approach this as a camera

00:14:53.100 --> 00:14:55.330
solution or as a
film solution.

00:14:55.330 --> 00:14:59.970
He was just looking outside
of the typical field.

00:14:59.970 --> 00:15:03.700
And I think a lot of the people
that I interviewed

00:15:03.700 --> 00:15:06.630
found solutions in
other venues.

00:15:06.630 --> 00:15:08.460
Sharing ideas with others.

00:15:08.460 --> 00:15:10.790
"Motivating a group to be
creative is not difficult.

00:15:10.790 --> 00:15:13.320
I believe that sharing ideas
is the secret to developing

00:15:13.320 --> 00:15:14.390
new concepts.

00:15:14.390 --> 00:15:16.740
If you can create an atmosphere
of honestly sharing

00:15:16.740 --> 00:15:19.520
whatever comes to your mind, I
don't care how brilliant you

00:15:19.520 --> 00:15:21.230
are, or how slow thinking
anybody is.

00:15:21.230 --> 00:15:24.080
If they're willing to open up
and let whatever they say or

00:15:24.080 --> 00:15:27.050
think come to the floor and
share with everyone else, even

00:15:27.050 --> 00:15:29.010
if it's the stupidest idea,
and they know it's stupid,

00:15:29.010 --> 00:15:31.850
when they say it, it often
leads to something.

00:15:31.850 --> 00:15:33.670
When you get two, three, or
four people together in a

00:15:33.670 --> 00:15:36.560
room, and you just open up and
say whatever you're thinking,

00:15:36.560 --> 00:15:38.050
good things will happen."

00:15:38.050 --> 00:15:42.260
So Reyn Guyer, the Nerf ball.

00:15:42.260 --> 00:15:44.140
I mean, it's the Nerf ball.

00:15:44.140 --> 00:15:46.850
I mean, this is the other
extreme of what

00:15:46.850 --> 00:15:48.160
invention is all about.

00:15:48.160 --> 00:15:50.840
And what the guy invented before
the Nerf ball, because

00:15:50.840 --> 00:15:51.750
it was all about playing?

00:15:51.750 --> 00:15:53.860
He invented the Twister game.

00:15:53.860 --> 00:15:55.670
And I think that's actually
even a more

00:15:55.670 --> 00:15:56.810
amazing thing, because--

00:15:56.810 --> 00:15:59.450
and this is pretty dated, but
back in the mid '60s when he

00:15:59.450 --> 00:16:03.040
developed this, society was
much more restrained and

00:16:03.040 --> 00:16:03.750
conservative.

00:16:03.750 --> 00:16:06.530
But basically, Twister opened up
where people could actually

00:16:06.530 --> 00:16:09.120
touch each other and physically
interact with each

00:16:09.120 --> 00:16:11.980
other, really changing the
social dynamics of society in

00:16:11.980 --> 00:16:13.790
something what he was doing.

00:16:13.790 --> 00:16:16.700
So able to visualize ideas in
their heads. "I visualize in

00:16:16.700 --> 00:16:19.010
three dimensions what the
products look like, and being

00:16:19.010 --> 00:16:21.120
such a hands-on builder of
products, I like to very

00:16:21.120 --> 00:16:23.570
quickly get into the three
dimensional form.

00:16:23.570 --> 00:16:25.820
I spend half an hour on a simple
sketch, then get right

00:16:25.820 --> 00:16:27.580
into trying to build something,
either carving out

00:16:27.580 --> 00:16:31.660
of foam with a rasp, or building
Bondo onto a last

00:16:31.660 --> 00:16:32.380
shape."

00:16:32.380 --> 00:16:34.000
Martin Keen with
Keen Footwear.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:36.400
Anybody know Keen Footwear?

00:16:36.400 --> 00:16:40.560
So, totally changed how shoes
look, but really changed how

00:16:40.560 --> 00:16:42.540
shoes feel.

00:16:42.540 --> 00:16:44.390
So he's an industrial
designer also.

00:16:44.390 --> 00:16:46.880
So very hands-on type
of guy, as I am.

00:16:46.880 --> 00:16:51.560
So before, the way shoes were
designed where the factory

00:16:51.560 --> 00:16:53.450
would have the last, which
is the shoe shape.

00:16:53.450 --> 00:16:56.840
They would give it to the
designer, this generic shape

00:16:56.840 --> 00:16:57.820
of all different sizes.

00:16:57.820 --> 00:17:00.360
And they would just sort of
design around the shoe last.

00:17:00.360 --> 00:17:03.660
What he did, he actually went
out and cast people's feet.

00:17:03.660 --> 00:17:06.520
Now, it sounds so obvious to
do something like that, but

00:17:06.520 --> 00:17:08.380
the designers never really
had that option

00:17:08.380 --> 00:17:09.960
before, to be that hands-on.

00:17:09.960 --> 00:17:13.490
And because of that, if you've
ever worn Keen Footwear, they

00:17:13.490 --> 00:17:14.930
really fit a lot better.

00:17:14.930 --> 00:17:16.200
And they're really
comfortable.

00:17:16.200 --> 00:17:19.210
And now, if you look at the way
shoes are, certainly the

00:17:19.210 --> 00:17:21.250
toe shape, they really have
changed because of what he's

00:17:21.250 --> 00:17:22.599
put in there.

00:17:22.599 --> 00:17:23.750
A touch of obsession.

