I think the key way that we
approach research, certainly

00:22:30.090 --> 00:22:32.970
on our more applied programs, is
that we want to get aligned

00:22:32.970 --> 00:22:35.140
with the right problem, So I
think it's fair to say that a

00:22:35.140 --> 00:22:39.030
lot of the biggest challenges
in doing innovation is

00:22:39.030 --> 00:22:41.700
tackling or asking the right
question, identifying the

00:22:41.700 --> 00:22:43.540
right problem."

00:22:43.540 --> 00:22:46.090
So Glen is at General
Electric.

00:22:46.090 --> 00:22:48.020
They're developing these
hybrid batteries for

00:22:48.020 --> 00:22:50.990
locomotives to eventually
run on batteries,

00:22:50.990 --> 00:22:54.030
not diesel fuel anymore.

00:22:54.030 --> 00:22:56.400
What was interesting about
Glenn is that he works at

00:22:56.400 --> 00:22:57.130
General Electric.

00:22:57.130 --> 00:22:59.410
And if you look at the inventing
process, and if you

00:22:59.410 --> 00:23:02.260
look at the king of inventor,
that's Thomas Edison.

00:23:02.260 --> 00:23:04.510
Just one thing he said to me,
when they walk into their

00:23:04.510 --> 00:23:07.500
door, Thomas Edison's
desk is right there.

00:23:07.500 --> 00:23:10.600
And just that heritage just
drove these people for

00:23:10.600 --> 00:23:14.390
perfection, and just keep
pushing themselves, and to

00:23:14.390 --> 00:23:16.190
really say what's out there.

00:23:16.190 --> 00:23:17.990
Also, General Electric
was really probably

00:23:17.990 --> 00:23:19.290
the first R&amp;D lab.

00:23:19.290 --> 00:23:22.320
So it went from being the lone
crazy guy in the garage to

00:23:22.320 --> 00:23:23.900
setting up in a corporate
atmosphere--

00:23:23.900 --> 00:23:26.830
in a sense, where
you are today.

00:23:26.830 --> 00:23:29.490
Prototype quickly. "Yes, I'm
going to stick my finger into

00:23:29.490 --> 00:23:31.230
a moving table saw blade.

00:23:31.230 --> 00:23:33.170
Your whole life, you have been
told not to do that.

00:23:33.170 --> 00:23:35.210
Your body is telling you,
no, don't do this.

00:23:35.210 --> 00:23:36.400
This is stupid."

00:23:36.400 --> 00:23:39.830
So I don't know if anybody's
heard of a saw stop table saw,

00:23:39.830 --> 00:23:42.690
or ever seen a demonstration,
or has anybody done

00:23:42.690 --> 00:23:44.220
woodworking before?

00:23:44.220 --> 00:23:46.840
And so you know that blade is
spinning really fast, and your

00:23:46.840 --> 00:23:48.150
fingers are getting
really close.

00:23:48.150 --> 00:23:52.280
So he's developed a saw that,
when it comes into contact

00:23:52.280 --> 00:23:55.050
with any part of the body, will
stop in 1/10,000 of a

00:23:55.050 --> 00:23:56.690
second, and will not cut
your finger off.

00:23:56.690 --> 00:24:00.570
What was interesting is that the
industry has, for years,

00:24:00.570 --> 00:24:03.110
sort of acknowledging the
problem, but sort of putting a

00:24:03.110 --> 00:24:05.150
guard on that they know everyone
will take off,

00:24:05.150 --> 00:24:06.630
because it just gets
in the way.

00:24:06.630 --> 00:24:08.580
But since no one had
solved the problem,

00:24:08.580 --> 00:24:09.850
that was the solution.

00:24:09.850 --> 00:24:11.340
Everyone said, just be careful,

00:24:11.340 --> 00:24:12.960
wear your safety goggles.

00:24:12.960 --> 00:24:16.200
His background was he actually
has a PhD in physics, but

00:24:16.200 --> 00:24:18.385
didn't want to teach, so went
back to school to become a

00:24:18.385 --> 00:24:19.970
patent attorney.

00:24:19.970 --> 00:24:22.910
And then was doing woodworking
on the side, and then

00:24:22.910 --> 00:24:25.530
realized, here's
a problem here.

00:24:25.530 --> 00:24:29.810
And when he was explaining the
process to me, he didn't look

00:24:29.810 --> 00:24:32.310
at this from a mechanical
standpoint at all.

00:24:32.310 --> 00:24:33.140
He just looked at it.

00:24:33.140 --> 00:24:37.975
He's a physicist, and he just
had these facts in his head

00:24:37.975 --> 00:24:40.720
that because I'm a physicist,
I know this, this, and this,

00:24:40.720 --> 00:24:42.240
and of course it should work.

00:24:42.240 --> 00:24:44.745
And so we had this whole
discussion, and literally, in

00:24:44.745 --> 00:24:46.820
a half hour, he said he
prototyped this thing.

00:24:46.820 --> 00:24:49.840
And then I said, well, how did
you decide to test this?

00:24:49.840 --> 00:24:52.040
And he goes, well, the first
one is we used a

00:24:52.040 --> 00:24:54.100
hot dog, and it worked.

00:24:54.100 --> 00:24:56.620
But then I'm obligated to stick
my finger into this

00:24:56.620 --> 00:24:59.220
thing, which I can't really
imagine that, because I do

00:24:59.220 --> 00:25:01.580
woodworking too.

00:25:01.580 --> 00:25:03.620
The conversation sort
of branched out.

00:25:03.620 --> 00:25:05.450
Like, I wasn't asking questions,
I just wanted to

00:25:05.450 --> 00:25:08.750
know, like, which finger did
you use to stick in it?

00:25:08.750 --> 00:25:10.463
And so we talked about it.

00:25:10.463 --> 00:25:12.020
And he goes, well, I'm right
handed, so it's going

00:25:12.020 --> 00:25:12.900
to be my left hand.

00:25:12.900 --> 00:25:15.610
He says, I need my thumb and
my pinky, because you don't

00:25:15.610 --> 00:25:17.070
want to keep hitting those.

00:25:17.070 --> 00:25:20.910
And you need your pointer
finger to do stuff with.

00:25:20.910 --> 00:25:23.630
And then I said, well you need
this finger, because it's the

00:25:23.630 --> 00:25:24.780
most important thing.

00:25:24.780 --> 00:25:25.760
And he goes yeah.

00:25:25.760 --> 00:25:27.620
So he actually chose
his ring finger.

00:25:27.620 --> 00:25:29.830
And as a pure engineer, it's
like, he didn't really need

00:25:29.830 --> 00:25:30.900
his wedding band.

00:25:30.900 --> 00:25:32.830
Even though he was married, it
didn't really matter if he cut

00:25:32.830 --> 00:25:33.720
that finger off.

00:25:33.720 --> 00:25:38.000
So he actually did stick his
ring finger into the table

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:38.800
saw, and it did work,.

00:25:38.800 --> 00:25:41.460
And now they control
80% of the market.

00:25:41.460 --> 00:25:44.690
And turned down by the whole
industry, but really

00:25:44.690 --> 00:25:46.910
controlling it now.

00:25:46.910 --> 00:25:48.420
Physical exercise.

00:25:48.420 --> 00:25:50.170
"Research proves the
role of exercise in

00:25:50.170 --> 00:25:51.270
keeping your brain vital.

00:25:51.270 --> 00:25:53.310
I do all sorts of
cardio exercise.

00:25:53.310 --> 00:25:56.140
I have advanced arthritis in one
hip, but I just went out

00:25:56.140 --> 00:25:57.150
and ran four miles.

00:25:57.150 --> 00:26:00.420
Obsessive personalities such
as mine help in maintaining

00:26:00.420 --> 00:26:01.040
these pursuits.

00:26:01.040 --> 00:26:03.760
I like to think that my
obsessions are synergistic.

00:26:03.760 --> 00:26:07.080
When I go and run like crazy,
I come back and feel my body

00:26:07.080 --> 00:26:09.700
and brain are all oxygenated
and ready to work."

00:26:09.700 --> 00:26:11.270
So Bob works at Xerox.

00:26:11.270 --> 00:26:13.260
I assume you've all used
a Xerox machine.

00:26:13.260 --> 00:26:17.790
His optical printing is what
runs all these machines, and

00:26:17.790 --> 00:26:18.560
it's just fascinating.

00:26:18.560 --> 00:26:21.980
And I think all you people look
in pretty good shape.

00:26:21.980 --> 00:26:23.790
You're riding bikes,
you're running,

00:26:23.790 --> 00:26:25.110
you're hiking mountains.

00:26:25.110 --> 00:26:27.680
And we all know we sort of get
that endorphin rush when we're

00:26:27.680 --> 00:26:29.000
out there doing something.

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:31.250
And I know, personally, because
I do a lot of cycling,

00:26:31.250 --> 00:26:33.720
that when I'm on my bike, I do
some of my best thinking,

00:26:33.720 --> 00:26:35.380
which is somewhat
contradictory.

00:26:35.380 --> 00:26:37.440
I should be doing my best
thinking when I'm sitting down

00:26:37.440 --> 00:26:38.920
in front of a piece of paper.

00:26:38.920 --> 00:26:42.170
But somehow, when your body
has had this relaxation

00:26:42.170 --> 00:26:44.020
process, you get
into this zone.

00:26:44.020 --> 00:26:48.690
And so these guys feel that
physical exercise is good.

00:26:48.690 --> 00:26:52.680
"Never retire from inventing."
So Kevin thinks maybe when

00:26:52.680 --> 00:26:54.400
he's dead, he's going
to retire.

00:26:54.400 --> 00:26:57.560
So he's a research mechanical
engineer at Monsanto.

00:26:57.560 --> 00:26:59.930
And whatever you want to think
about Monsanto, that's a whole

00:26:59.930 --> 00:27:01.310
other discussion.

00:27:01.310 --> 00:27:04.360
So what he's figured out is a
machine to actually read the

00:27:04.360 --> 00:27:06.430
DNA a of a seed before
it's planted.

00:27:06.430 --> 00:27:09.150
So it's taking a tiny little
scraping off of the seed, and

00:27:09.150 --> 00:27:11.480
then will figure out how to
read it in a very quick

00:27:11.480 --> 00:27:12.880
automated process.

00:27:12.880 --> 00:27:15.690
And so I asked him, well,
how do you think?

00:27:15.690 --> 00:27:16.960
How did you come up
with this idea?

00:27:16.960 --> 00:27:19.540
He goes, well, my office
is in Saint Louis.

00:27:19.540 --> 00:27:20.700
The fields are in Iowa.

00:27:20.700 --> 00:27:22.370
It's a five or six hour drive.

00:27:22.370 --> 00:27:24.790
I have to go out there once a
month, and I'm driving five or

00:27:24.790 --> 00:27:25.930
six hours by myself.

00:27:25.930 --> 00:27:29.210
And I said, I picture
myself as the seed.

00:27:29.210 --> 00:27:32.820
I'm in the ground, and the
dirt's above me, and the sun's

00:27:32.820 --> 00:27:34.880
above me, and the rain's
coming down.

00:27:34.880 --> 00:27:37.370
And I say to myself, if
I was a seed, what I

00:27:37.370 --> 00:27:38.260
would want to be.

00:27:38.260 --> 00:27:40.230
And just the focus and
the concentration

00:27:40.230 --> 00:27:41.730
was just really good.

00:27:41.730 --> 00:27:44.170
And I think sometimes you have
to see the big picture.

00:27:44.170 --> 00:27:48.050
But here he is just getting
really small, and really

00:27:48.050 --> 00:27:49.160
looking what he was doing.

00:27:49.160 --> 00:27:52.800
And he said to me, he's
like, I get paid.

00:27:52.800 --> 00:27:54.120
I don't even know
what I get paid.

00:27:54.120 --> 00:27:57.290
My check gets deposited, but
I have enough money.

00:27:57.290 --> 00:27:59.450
And I just want to keep
doing this forever.

00:27:59.450 --> 00:28:00.880
It was also interesting.

00:28:00.880 --> 00:28:03.170
This guy, originally
he was in the army.

00:28:03.170 --> 00:28:04.250
He went back to school after.

00:28:04.250 --> 00:28:07.560
He went to community college,
took some engineering classes,

00:28:07.560 --> 00:28:09.740
and then eventually went
back to school again.

00:28:09.740 --> 00:28:13.440
And so some of these people just
were self trained people.

00:28:13.440 --> 00:28:16.890
Some community college, people,
some are MIT trained,

00:28:16.890 --> 00:28:17.920
some have advanced degrees.

00:28:17.920 --> 00:28:19.900
So it's all facets.

00:28:19.900 --> 00:28:20.930
Making money.

00:28:20.930 --> 00:28:23.300
"If you make no money with your
invention, basically you

00:28:23.300 --> 00:28:25.360
really failed in the
real world."

00:28:25.360 --> 00:28:27.260
And this was Ron Popeil.

00:28:27.260 --> 00:28:30.990
I'm sure you guys have seen Ron
Popeil on TV selling his

00:28:30.990 --> 00:28:33.560
Chopomatic or his Pocket
Fisherman.

00:28:33.560 --> 00:28:36.970
So he's still alive there, and
actually has been retired.

00:28:36.970 --> 00:28:39.110
He sold his company a number
of years ago,.

00:28:39.110 --> 00:28:43.390
And he has a new kitchen turkey
fryer that the whole

00:28:43.390 --> 00:28:45.510
time while I'm interviewing,
he's trying to sell me his

00:28:45.510 --> 00:28:51.340
turkey fryer, which was
really interesting.

00:28:51.340 --> 00:28:54.740
And he cooks everything, so
he was just making it.

00:28:54.740 --> 00:28:56.320
It sounded so good.

00:28:56.320 --> 00:28:57.880
He goes to the other extreme.

00:28:57.880 --> 00:29:00.530
So his whole validation
is on money.

00:29:00.530 --> 00:29:02.370
And I thought that was really
interesting, because all these

00:29:02.370 --> 00:29:05.370
other people, their validation
was on the success of their

00:29:05.370 --> 00:29:08.220
project, the invention
and it helps society.

00:29:08.220 --> 00:29:11.090
And he looked at as like, well,
if everyone's giving me

00:29:11.090 --> 00:29:13.620
money, they're all using my
product, and they're getting

00:29:13.620 --> 00:29:15.130
the advantage of that.

00:29:15.130 --> 00:29:17.090
Though he never really looked at
the quality of what he was

00:29:17.090 --> 00:29:19.290
doing, he just looked at the
quantity of what he was doing.

00:29:19.290 --> 00:29:22.020
But I think it was just
fascinating listening to the

00:29:22.020 --> 00:29:24.360
other extreme of what's
out there.

00:29:24.360 --> 00:29:25.100
And so patents.

00:29:25.100 --> 00:29:29.220
So I interviewed 23 people--

00:29:29.220 --> 00:29:30.920
23 chapters, I should say.

00:29:30.920 --> 00:29:32.080
Some were multiple people.

00:29:32.080 --> 00:29:35.250
22 of them were inventors, and
the last two, Elizabeth and

00:29:35.250 --> 00:29:36.980
John, were assistant
commissioners

00:29:36.980 --> 00:29:38.570
at the patent office.

00:29:38.570 --> 00:29:41.220
And I wanted to know,
really, about so the

00:29:41.220 --> 00:29:42.210
question about patents.

00:29:42.210 --> 00:29:45.410
Because IP is really important
to all of us, whether it's

00:29:45.410 --> 00:29:47.170
hardware or software.

00:29:47.170 --> 00:29:50.640
And these two people are now
working with individual

00:29:50.640 --> 00:29:52.600
inventors and small
businesses.

00:29:52.600 --> 00:29:54.660
"Throughout our history, people
have come to America

00:29:54.660 --> 00:29:57.420
looking for their freedom and
opportunity to be independent,

00:29:57.420 --> 00:29:58.850
create something on their
own, and claim a

00:29:58.850 --> 00:30:00.300
piece of the universe.

00:30:00.300 --> 00:30:02.750
This quest has driven our
success as a nation.

00:30:02.750 --> 00:30:04.990
Our office aims to make
inventors realize that there

00:30:04.990 --> 00:30:07.820
is assistance here for them as
they begin their innovative

00:30:07.820 --> 00:30:08.240
journey."

00:30:08.240 --> 00:30:10.930
I mean, what's great about this
country, and what has

00:30:10.930 --> 00:30:12.690
made this country is
innovation, that

00:30:12.690 --> 00:30:14.030
we have this freedom.

00:30:14.030 --> 00:30:16.420
And the biggest freedom, I
think, is that you could fail.

00:30:16.420 --> 00:30:18.910
You can make a zillion mistakes,
but yet, if you

00:30:18.910 --> 00:30:21.960
achieve, you could be rewarded
for those things.

00:30:21.960 --> 00:30:23.440
And you have that
ability there.

00:30:23.440 --> 00:30:24.810
And so the patent office--

00:30:24.810 --> 00:30:27.820
and everyone has a different
opinion on that, the good and

00:30:27.820 --> 00:30:30.060
bad of patents, and I know
everyone is fighting in the

00:30:30.060 --> 00:30:31.350
courts right now.

00:30:31.350 --> 00:30:35.310
But patents, these guys are at
least there to help protect

00:30:35.310 --> 00:30:36.070
the small business.

00:30:36.070 --> 00:30:38.330
So if you guys do have
ideas, you don't

00:30:38.330 --> 00:30:40.310
have to hire attorneys.

00:30:40.310 --> 00:30:41.300
You could do it pro se.

00:30:41.300 --> 00:30:43.600
They're having new programs that
they're establishing all

00:30:43.600 --> 00:30:46.280
over the country at local
community colleges to help

00:30:46.280 --> 00:30:49.640
people submit a patent pro se,
which just meaning submitting

00:30:49.640 --> 00:30:50.660
to yourself.

00:30:50.660 --> 00:30:53.750
So some of the things that I've
learned just in my career

00:30:53.750 --> 00:30:54.770
as an inventor--

00:30:54.770 --> 00:30:57.280
we're fascinated, we have
to do something new.

00:30:57.280 --> 00:30:59.590
And personally, that's a lot
of pressure to put on

00:30:59.590 --> 00:31:00.980
yourself, doing that.

00:31:00.980 --> 00:31:03.750
So I think the way I've come to
terms with that-- the only

00:31:03.750 --> 00:31:07.390
thing that was ever new was the
wheel, the hammer, and the

00:31:07.390 --> 00:31:08.950
process of making fire.

00:31:08.950 --> 00:31:11.040
And if you have those three
variables, heat,

00:31:11.040 --> 00:31:12.250
pressure, and time--

00:31:12.250 --> 00:31:14.470
and from those heat, pressure,
and time, you could create

00:31:14.470 --> 00:31:15.710
anything after that.

00:31:15.710 --> 00:31:18.890
So I never really looked that
I'm doing something new.

00:31:18.890 --> 00:31:22.180
What I think I'm doing is trying
to modify stuff, and

00:31:22.180 --> 00:31:24.330
try to sort of see what
was done before, and

00:31:24.330 --> 00:31:25.410
what is the next step?

00:31:25.410 --> 00:31:27.775
Because after I'm long and
gone, there's going to be

00:31:27.775 --> 00:31:30.540
someone after me who's going to
look at what I did and do

00:31:30.540 --> 00:31:32.650
the next generation of stuff.

00:31:32.650 --> 00:31:34.570
And I also think it's
a challenge.

00:31:34.570 --> 00:31:37.020
When you think something
is new, people

00:31:37.020 --> 00:31:37.800
really won't get it.

00:31:37.800 --> 00:31:40.460
I mean, there's always the first
adopters, but that's a

00:31:40.460 --> 00:31:41.530
very small percentage.

00:31:41.530 --> 00:31:45.400
So I think it's important to
understand and pay homage to

00:31:45.400 --> 00:31:47.560
what someone did before, and
go to the next step.

00:31:47.560 --> 00:31:49.900
But never think that it's going
to be so different that

00:31:49.900 --> 00:31:51.740
it's never been done
before, because

00:31:51.740 --> 00:31:53.470
everything has been done.

00:31:53.470 --> 00:31:55.370
And so what does it mean
to be creative?

00:31:55.370 --> 00:31:58.620
And to me, I think society says
that you can draw pretty

00:31:58.620 --> 00:32:01.060
pictures, you can play an
instrument, or you can act or

00:32:01.060 --> 00:32:02.000
whatever it may be.

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:04.870
But to me, creativity is all
about problem solving.

00:32:04.870 --> 00:32:05.680
It's that simple.

00:32:05.680 --> 00:32:06.375
That's the definition.

00:32:06.375 --> 00:32:08.090
It's just problem solving.

00:32:08.090 --> 00:32:11.570
And it's important, I think, as
Glen from General Electric

00:32:11.570 --> 00:32:14.200
said, it's important to really
define what the problem is

00:32:14.200 --> 00:32:16.910
that you're going to solve, and
then go back and make sure

00:32:16.910 --> 00:32:18.310
there's an equal sign.

00:32:18.310 --> 00:32:19.480
So innovation.

00:32:19.480 --> 00:32:25.250
Big buzzword right now, as
compared to what is invention

00:32:25.250 --> 00:32:26.120
or innovation?

00:32:26.120 --> 00:32:28.050
So to me, innovation is the

00:32:28.050 --> 00:32:30.350
commercialization of that idea.

00:32:30.350 --> 00:32:34.610
It's not the idea, it's just how
you get it out there into

00:32:34.610 --> 00:32:37.920
the marketplace, and the
marketing of it.

00:32:37.920 --> 00:32:40.810
And the invention side is the
understanding and the

00:32:40.810 --> 00:32:44.430
reinterpretation of scientific
or technical data.

00:32:44.430 --> 00:32:47.180
And so, if you're inventing
something, you really have to

00:32:47.180 --> 00:32:49.360
understand how it works,
how it's made, the

00:32:49.360 --> 00:32:51.310
materials, and so forth.

00:32:51.310 --> 00:32:54.650
This is just sort of
a personal thing.

00:32:54.650 --> 00:32:57.515
To be an innovative person, to
be an inventive person, to be

00:32:57.515 --> 00:33:00.940
a creative person, you need to
be flexible, whether that's

00:33:00.940 --> 00:33:04.200
intellectually, emotionally,
physically.

00:33:04.200 --> 00:33:06.470
You just need to be adaptable
all the time.

00:33:06.470 --> 00:33:09.080
You may have sort of a solution,
and you go down that

00:33:09.080 --> 00:33:11.910
road, and it may not work, but
you need to be able to adapt

00:33:11.910 --> 00:33:14.470
continuously to say,
oh, I could change.

00:33:14.470 --> 00:33:16.800
And I think that's just, as
you get older, it becomes

00:33:16.800 --> 00:33:18.100
harder to change.

00:33:18.100 --> 00:33:20.900
And so you have to sort
of resist all that and

00:33:20.900 --> 00:33:22.150
continuously be flexible.

00:33:24.820 --> 00:33:26.410
There are adrenaline junkies.

00:33:26.410 --> 00:33:28.100
I'm an experience junkie.

00:33:28.100 --> 00:33:30.190
And so I've jumped out of
a plane, so I don't

00:33:30.190 --> 00:33:31.680
need to do it again.

00:33:31.680 --> 00:33:33.660
But I just love having different
experiences.

00:33:33.660 --> 00:33:36.695
And sometimes it's just eating
a meal or eating a food that

00:33:36.695 --> 00:33:37.920
I've never had before.

00:33:37.920 --> 00:33:40.360
But it's just all these
experiences add up to

00:33:40.360 --> 00:33:44.460
opportunities and situations
that you could reference from.

00:33:44.460 --> 00:33:49.480
And this is time I've come to
know that it doesn't matter

00:33:49.480 --> 00:33:52.400
how smart you are or how much
money you have, this is the

00:33:52.400 --> 00:33:55.130
only thing in the world that
is limited and you cannot

00:33:55.130 --> 00:33:56.270
create more of.

00:33:56.270 --> 00:33:59.160
No one will ever create more
time, so use it wisely.

00:33:59.160 --> 00:34:02.290
I mean, it's important to look
long term down the road.

00:34:02.290 --> 00:34:04.740
But as John Maynard Keynes
said, in the long

00:34:04.740 --> 00:34:05.870
term, you're dead.

00:34:05.870 --> 00:34:07.820
And that will happen
eventually.

00:34:07.820 --> 00:34:11.080
And so use your time wisely
and really focus on what

00:34:11.080 --> 00:34:13.130
you're doing at the moment.

00:34:13.130 --> 00:34:15.480
If you're putting stuff out
there, I'm sure you guys think

00:34:15.480 --> 00:34:17.650
about this all the time--
telling a good story.

00:34:17.650 --> 00:34:20.590
You want people to buy into
what you're doing.

00:34:20.590 --> 00:34:24.489
And so I have actually put
products out on my own, which

00:34:24.489 --> 00:34:26.730
is a lot different than
inventing something and

00:34:26.730 --> 00:34:30.860
handing it off to the client
or your boss or something.

00:34:30.860 --> 00:34:33.610
And to me, being an entrepreneur
is just whatever

00:34:33.610 --> 00:34:36.460
it is, it's taking full
responsibility for everything.

00:34:36.460 --> 00:34:40.020
If there's a hurricane on the
east coast, it's your

00:34:40.020 --> 00:34:41.460
responsibility if you're
trying to get

00:34:41.460 --> 00:34:42.489
your product there.

00:34:42.489 --> 00:34:45.070
If your employee doesn't
deliver, it's your

00:34:45.070 --> 00:34:46.190
responsibility.

00:34:46.190 --> 00:34:49.520
So being an entrepreneur means
taking full responsibility for

00:34:49.520 --> 00:34:50.969
everything.

00:34:50.969 --> 00:34:54.570
And so this is something that
a lot of beers I've come up

00:34:54.570 --> 00:34:56.190
with this quote.

00:34:56.190 --> 00:34:58.110
"A man climbs a mountain
because it's there.

00:34:58.110 --> 00:35:00.040
A man invents something because
it's not there."

00:35:00.040 --> 00:35:01.640
And this is just sort of
something in your gut.

00:35:01.640 --> 00:35:02.940
It's like, I'm going
to do this, because

00:35:02.940 --> 00:35:04.500
it's never been done.

00:35:04.500 --> 00:35:07.060
I don't know why, it's just some
people like doing this.

00:35:07.060 --> 00:35:08.330
And I have that.

00:35:08.330 --> 00:35:11.600
And all these other
people have that.

00:35:11.600 --> 00:35:14.420
So that's my presentation.

00:35:14.420 --> 00:35:17.230
I hope we have some
questions now.

00:35:17.230 --> 00:35:19.970
So the question is, how do
ethics get involved?

00:35:19.970 --> 00:35:20.260
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:35:20.260 --> 00:35:23.724
To what extent is an inventor
responsible for the ethical

00:35:23.724 --> 00:35:25.137
implications of [INAUDIBLE]?

00:35:25.137 --> 00:35:26.820
BRETT STERN: I would say,
and I'm going to

00:35:26.820 --> 00:35:28.620
speak for myself now--

00:35:28.620 --> 00:35:34.000
I do what I do because my
parents gave me certain values

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:35.090
and ethics.

00:35:35.090 --> 00:35:39.490
And I'm committed to making the
world a better place in a

00:35:39.490 --> 00:35:40.540
positive way.

00:35:40.540 --> 00:35:42.520
That's just me personally.

00:35:42.520 --> 00:35:44.830
And the things I'm trying
to do, I think,

00:35:44.830 --> 00:35:46.300
are helping the world.

00:35:46.300 --> 00:35:52.220
And when I do a surgical
instrument, those things came

00:35:52.220 --> 00:35:53.190
in front of me all day.

00:35:53.190 --> 00:35:56.610
Like, are you extending
someone's life to be good, or

00:35:56.610 --> 00:35:57.920
should they just die?

00:35:57.920 --> 00:36:01.120
And these were issues
I'd faced.

00:36:01.120 --> 00:36:02.090
It's a challenge.

00:36:02.090 --> 00:36:02.710
I don't know.

00:36:02.710 --> 00:36:04.110
I don't really have an answer.

00:36:04.110 --> 00:36:07.200
I think you have to think of
them, and I think you have to

00:36:07.200 --> 00:36:10.310
just personally say to
yourself, do I feel

00:36:10.310 --> 00:36:12.800
comfortable putting this out
there in the marketplace?

00:36:12.800 --> 00:36:16.940
That being said, when you give
someone a tool, whether it's

00:36:16.940 --> 00:36:20.540
digital or analog, you have no
control over how they're

00:36:20.540 --> 00:36:22.500
going to use it.

00:36:22.500 --> 00:36:25.710
And to not put it out there,
to prevent it out there, I

00:36:25.710 --> 00:36:29.120
mean, once you open up that
box, it's out there.

00:36:29.120 --> 00:36:30.430
You have no control over it.

00:36:30.430 --> 00:36:33.690
And good things can
be used for bad.

00:36:33.690 --> 00:36:34.670
I don't have an answer.

00:36:34.670 --> 00:36:37.430
I think it's just on a
case by case basis.

00:36:37.430 --> 00:36:40.620
You have to feel comfortable
with yourself.

00:36:40.620 --> 00:36:44.470
You can't live in
a pure world.

00:36:44.470 --> 00:36:45.690
it's just not pure anymore.

00:36:45.690 --> 00:36:49.510
You just have to put it out
there, do your best, and

00:36:49.510 --> 00:36:53.000
hopefully it'll be used
for the good of man.

00:36:53.000 --> 00:36:55.800
And that's the best
answer I can give.

00:36:55.800 --> 00:36:59.770
So you were asking me about what
is innovation, and why is

00:36:59.770 --> 00:37:02.170
it always commercialization
based?

00:37:02.170 --> 00:37:05.240
I think you could invent
something and not

00:37:05.240 --> 00:37:07.290
commercialize on it, not bring
it to the marketplace.

00:37:07.290 --> 00:37:10.280
You can have it sit in your
garage, and that's fine.

00:37:10.280 --> 00:37:11.440
It's your decision.

00:37:11.440 --> 00:37:16.270
I think the reason I wanted
to give that definition is

00:37:16.270 --> 00:37:19.750
because I think the term
inventing, invention,

00:37:19.750 --> 00:37:22.760
creativity, innovative, they're
just terms thrown out

00:37:22.760 --> 00:37:23.620
there all day.

00:37:23.620 --> 00:37:26.810
And hanging out with like-minded
people, we're in

00:37:26.810 --> 00:37:29.250
bars, and we're discussing
our projects, and it

00:37:29.250 --> 00:37:29.910
always comes up.

00:37:29.910 --> 00:37:32.090
And it's like, well, I'm
creative, and I'm innovative.

00:37:32.090 --> 00:37:33.380
Well, is it the same thing?

00:37:33.380 --> 00:37:35.600
And what are the subtleties,
differences?

00:37:35.600 --> 00:37:38.350
And so I just made a definition
up for myself to

00:37:38.350 --> 00:37:41.520
sort of say, when I'm doing
projects, I'm doing the

00:37:41.520 --> 00:37:42.490
invention now.

00:37:42.490 --> 00:37:44.720
And now I'm doing
the innovation.

00:37:44.720 --> 00:37:46.300
And you're wearing
separate hats.

00:37:46.300 --> 00:37:48.230
Because when you're doing the
invention side, you're wearing

00:37:48.230 --> 00:37:50.635
the technical engineering
design hat.

00:37:50.635 --> 00:37:54.260
But I feel when you're wearing
the innovation hat, you're

00:37:54.260 --> 00:37:57.120
wearing the marketing and
the business side.

00:37:57.120 --> 00:38:00.310
And it just made me feel
comfortable to understand that

00:38:00.310 --> 00:38:01.320
they're two separate things.

00:38:01.320 --> 00:38:03.740
Because as a designer,
everything is all about

00:38:03.740 --> 00:38:04.950
compromise.

00:38:04.950 --> 00:38:06.790
When you're doing art, there's
no compromise.

00:38:06.790 --> 00:38:08.420
It's just what you're
doing for yourself.

00:38:08.420 --> 00:38:10.920
When you do design, it's
compromising things.

00:38:10.920 --> 00:38:15.520
And I think when you're doing
the innovation side, the

00:38:15.520 --> 00:38:17.950
invention side is done already,
and you're trying to

00:38:17.950 --> 00:38:18.930
get it out there.

00:38:18.930 --> 00:38:22.020
And frankly, I want people to
give me money for the things.

00:38:22.020 --> 00:38:23.990
I mean, you guys want people
to give you money for the

00:38:23.990 --> 00:38:26.220
things, too, whether it's
directly or indirectly.

00:38:26.220 --> 00:38:28.680
And you create situations where
people give you money

00:38:28.680 --> 00:38:29.690
for your things.

00:38:29.690 --> 00:38:30.580
And that's separate.

00:38:30.580 --> 00:38:33.480
You don't ask the same people
who are thinking of the

00:38:33.480 --> 00:38:37.290
technology side to figure out
ways to give you money side.

00:38:37.290 --> 00:38:39.720
You purposely separate
those two.

00:38:39.720 --> 00:38:41.360
And you have to wear two
different hats, because

00:38:41.360 --> 00:38:43.130
they're two different methods.

00:38:43.130 --> 00:38:45.650
So that's why I personally, just
me, personally-- again,

00:38:45.650 --> 00:38:47.050
it's my definition--

00:38:47.050 --> 00:38:48.520
is I'm able to separate that.

00:38:48.520 --> 00:38:50.340
It's like, OK, I've done
the invention side.

00:38:50.340 --> 00:38:52.310
Now I'm going to go out and
make some money doing it.

00:38:52.310 --> 00:38:55.800
And frankly, I like to be
compensated for my work.

00:38:55.800 --> 00:38:56.740
I think it's fair.

00:38:56.740 --> 00:38:59.380
Just as everyone else
gets compensated.

00:38:59.380 --> 00:39:04.400
So I realize that when I'm the
inventing side, I'm sort of

00:39:04.400 --> 00:39:07.150
looking very close down.

00:39:07.150 --> 00:39:08.610
I'm looking down at
the drawing board.

00:39:08.610 --> 00:39:11.180
And when I'm doing the
innovation side, I am sort of

00:39:11.180 --> 00:39:12.510
looking at the world
out there.

00:39:12.510 --> 00:39:14.240
I'm saying, hello,
can you hear me?

00:39:14.240 --> 00:39:16.660
So that's where I feel
comfortable.

00:39:16.660 --> 00:39:19.540
So what tips would I share
as an inventor?

00:39:19.540 --> 00:39:22.470
Well, I had the option of
interviewing myself, because

00:39:22.470 --> 00:39:25.630
some of the other "At Work"
books, they did exactly that.

00:39:25.630 --> 00:39:29.480
I thought it was surreal
to do that.

00:39:29.480 --> 00:39:35.250
And I felt, maybe, when I did
this project, I think I was

00:39:35.250 --> 00:39:36.200
looking for validation.

00:39:36.200 --> 00:39:38.270
Like, I've been doing
this for 25 years.

00:39:38.270 --> 00:39:39.570
Have I learned anything?

00:39:39.570 --> 00:39:43.090
And so these are the masters
and everything.

00:39:43.090 --> 00:39:45.960
So I felt I was giving
reverence to them.

00:39:45.960 --> 00:39:48.650
And when I got to the end of
it-- so all these things?

00:39:48.650 --> 00:39:50.890
All those skill sets?

00:39:50.890 --> 00:39:52.050
I have all those.

00:39:52.050 --> 00:39:53.940
So I felt pretty good
about myself.

00:39:53.940 --> 00:39:57.370
So I feel, yes, I'm
an inventor.

00:39:57.370 --> 00:39:58.950
I could get to wear
the inventor hat.

00:39:58.950 --> 00:40:02.050
Whether I have patents enough or
not, I'm still an inventor.

00:40:02.050 --> 00:40:03.530
I've made money on
my invention.

00:40:03.530 --> 00:40:06.480
So if you get a patent,
are you an inventor?

00:40:06.480 --> 00:40:07.830
If you make money, are
you an inventor?

00:40:07.830 --> 00:40:08.200
I don't know.

00:40:08.200 --> 00:40:09.910
I've done both those things.

00:40:09.910 --> 00:40:10.860
So what have I learned?

00:40:10.860 --> 00:40:12.850
I've learned all those
things on there.

00:40:12.850 --> 00:40:15.370
And I learned it's
a lifestyle.

00:40:15.370 --> 00:40:20.770
It's something that you're born
with and can be nurtured,

00:40:20.770 --> 00:40:24.030
but it's also something you have
to live with 24/7 that

00:40:24.030 --> 00:40:25.500
you just can't really
turn it off.

00:40:25.500 --> 00:40:30.960
And I think some professions
that you could go in at 9:00

00:40:30.960 --> 00:40:34.900
in the morning, hit the time
clock, and at 5:00, come home

00:40:34.900 --> 00:40:38.170
and go out with your buddies and
watch the game, whatever.

00:40:38.170 --> 00:40:39.990
And you could sort of
turn your brain off.

00:40:39.990 --> 00:40:40.860
This--

00:40:40.860 --> 00:40:43.800
and this is for all
creative people--

00:40:43.800 --> 00:40:44.740
it's a life thing.

00:40:44.740 --> 00:40:46.360
It's a 24/7 thing.

00:40:46.360 --> 00:40:52.220
And so that's the best thing I
could say to a young inventor,

00:40:52.220 --> 00:40:55.390
because I had these
conversations, is accept it.

00:40:55.390 --> 00:40:56.680
Just, you're weird.

00:40:56.680 --> 00:40:59.390
You think different than all the
other kids on the block.

00:40:59.390 --> 00:41:00.690
This is how you are.

00:41:00.690 --> 00:41:03.770
Try to be around with
like-minded people that don't

00:41:03.770 --> 00:41:05.890
think you're so weird and crazy,
that you're thinking

00:41:05.890 --> 00:41:07.220
all the time.

00:41:07.220 --> 00:41:09.890
But it's OK to think this way.

00:41:09.890 --> 00:41:13.850
And it's really quite
fun after a while.

00:41:13.850 --> 00:41:17.480
I've made it through life so far
without ever having a job.

00:41:17.480 --> 00:41:19.710
I've worked since I'm 14,
somehow, in the creative

00:41:19.710 --> 00:41:22.060
industries, but I've
never had a job.

00:41:22.060 --> 00:41:25.000
And I could say that
to other people.

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:26.600
Like, you could make a
living doing this.

00:41:26.600 --> 00:41:27.660
And it's not really a living.

00:41:27.660 --> 00:41:32.180
I mean, whatever money I make, I
blow it on the next project.

00:41:32.180 --> 00:41:33.830
And that's really
important to me.

00:41:33.830 --> 00:41:35.650
So I never get comfortable.

00:41:35.650 --> 00:41:37.250
I live a very simple life.

00:41:37.250 --> 00:41:39.810
I have a very low carbon
footprint.

00:41:39.810 --> 00:41:41.190
I'm a single guy.

00:41:41.190 --> 00:41:43.880
I could take everything that
I've made and just blow it on

00:41:43.880 --> 00:41:44.450
the next thing.

00:41:44.450 --> 00:41:46.620
The worst that can happen
is I could fail

00:41:46.620 --> 00:41:47.690
and I'll lose money.

00:41:47.690 --> 00:41:51.130
I'm not going to do anything
wrong or unethical or illegal.

00:41:51.130 --> 00:41:53.250
I know that I'm not going
to be put in jail.

00:41:53.250 --> 00:41:55.010
I pay my taxes like
everyone else.

00:41:55.010 --> 00:41:56.390
I have health insurance.

00:41:56.390 --> 00:42:01.590
But you can have this life
and live this way.

00:42:01.590 --> 00:42:02.020
It's great.

00:42:02.020 --> 00:42:04.650
And you could work in a
corporate setting, as a

00:42:04.650 --> 00:42:07.350
consulting setting, or as an
entrepreneurial setting.

00:42:07.350 --> 00:42:08.220
Whatever it may be.

00:42:08.220 --> 00:42:10.210
So go forth and prosper.

00:42:10.210 --> 00:42:11.420
It's possible.

00:42:11.420 --> 00:42:14.390
And I think with all the turmoil
we have today, whether

00:42:14.390 --> 00:42:17.400
in the world or in our country,
for whatever reasons,

00:42:17.400 --> 00:42:20.640
this is such a great time to
live, because whatever worked

00:42:20.640 --> 00:42:23.440
yesterday is not working
tomorrow.

00:42:23.440 --> 00:42:25.860
And I mean, it's just amazing.

00:42:25.860 --> 00:42:28.450
And it doesn't matter how old
you are or how young you are

00:42:28.450 --> 00:42:31.130
or what education you have,
there's always a way to get

00:42:31.130 --> 00:42:33.760
some money to do something,
whatever way it is.

00:42:33.760 --> 00:42:36.270
I mean, whether it's from your
parents, or a credit card, or

00:42:36.270 --> 00:42:38.760
VC, whatever, Kickstarter.

00:42:38.760 --> 00:42:42.380
There's ways to get money to
fund these projects to just go

00:42:42.380 --> 00:42:43.700
into the garage and
make something.

00:42:43.700 --> 00:42:47.110
Whether it's digital, analog,
this is the most amazing time

00:42:47.110 --> 00:42:47.820
to live right now.

00:42:47.820 --> 00:42:50.850
With all the tools that you guys
provide out there into

00:42:50.850 --> 00:42:53.530
the marketplace, and all the
technology and tools that

00:42:53.530 --> 00:42:56.960
these former guys have
developed and

00:42:56.960 --> 00:42:58.280
offered to our society.

00:42:58.280 --> 00:43:00.540
I mean, it's just so exciting
right now with all the

00:43:00.540 --> 00:43:04.940
materials and the technologies
and just things to try.

00:43:04.940 --> 00:43:08.290
And it doesn't have to
be fiber optics.

00:43:08.290 --> 00:43:10.510
It doesn't have to
be RAM memory.

00:43:10.510 --> 00:43:14.800
It could be a new bike light,
something like that.

00:43:14.800 --> 00:43:17.820
When the inventors created their
projects, were they also

00:43:17.820 --> 00:43:20.470
thinking of the innovation
side?

00:43:20.470 --> 00:43:21.670
Great question.

00:43:21.670 --> 00:43:26.110
And I would say most of the
people I interviewed were in a

00:43:26.110 --> 00:43:29.450
corporate or governmental
or educational setting.

00:43:29.450 --> 00:43:32.710
And so, especially in the
corporate setting, you have

00:43:32.710 --> 00:43:35.500
all these people out there to
do certain roles, and their

00:43:35.500 --> 00:43:37.680
job was to do the
invention side.

00:43:37.680 --> 00:43:39.960
They would talk with the
marketing side and the sales

00:43:39.960 --> 00:43:44.370
side continuously, and
especially nowadays, where the

00:43:44.370 --> 00:43:45.290
people are all brought in.

00:43:45.290 --> 00:43:48.300
In fact, they're bringing the
manufacturing people in.

00:43:48.300 --> 00:43:50.910
They're bringing everyone in
right from the beginning.

00:43:50.910 --> 00:43:53.900
But I would say the actual
inventors don't really have,

00:43:53.900 --> 00:43:56.440
in a corporate setting,
involvement in

00:43:56.440 --> 00:43:58.160
the innovation side.

00:43:58.160 --> 00:44:01.745
Tim Leatherman, as an example,
because he was the crazy guy

